003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish, English, and especially Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>graund</i>, <i>graunt</i> ‘tall, large’ (Old French <i>grand</i>, <i>grant</i>, from Latin <i>grandis</i>), given either to a person of remarkable size, or else in a relative way to distinguish two bearers of the same personal name, often representatives of different generations within the same family.","English: from the rare Middle English (and Old English) personal name <i>Grante</i> or <i>Grente</i>.","Irish: in Ireland this is usually the Norman Scottish name (see 1 above), but it was also adopted for Irish <b>Mag Raighne</b>, see   Graney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Graney","meanings":["Irish (Galway, Cork, and Kerry): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Raighne</b> ‘son of <i>Raighne</i>’, a pet form of <i>Raghnall</i>. It has sometimes been changed to   Grant  . See also   Rainey  .","Possibly an altered form of Swiss German <b>Gräni</b>, unexplained."]},{"name":"Grand","meanings":["French: nickname from Old French <i>grand</i>, <i>grant</i> ‘tall, large’, from Latin <i>grandis</i>. See also   Grant   1 and 4, compare   Degrand   and   Legrand  .","German: topographic name for someone who lived in a gravelly area, from Middle Low German <i>grand</i> ‘coarse gravel’.","German: nickname from a southern word of uncertain origin meaning ‘frustration, anger, ire’."]},{"name":"Grande","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Rocco, Domenic, Mario, Antonio, Santo, Orlando, Americo, Carmine, Gennaro, Luigi, Pasquale, Saverio, Alberico.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Alicia, Ricardo, Jorge, Juan, Raul, Angel, Atilio.","Italian, Spanish, and Portuguese: nickname for someone of large stature, in either a literal or figurative sense, from <i>grande</i> ‘tall, large’.","German: habitational name from Grande in Holstein or Grand in Bavaria."]},{"name":"General","meanings":["African American: from the English vocabulary word 